fields.title: Begin
fields.content1: 9 Finance is alive and registered as a partnership. Domain name nine.finance is bought. Initial research on light bulb idea continued and team search fully began based on requirements proposed.
fields.content2: We all have ideas. Sometimes all you need is an little push. Starting is one of the things that separates us from others. Those who do and those who do not. The rest is history.
fields.content3: We regularly discussed business ideas, but this one was different. One eventful day, while I was high as fuck at home, my bro asked me if I could come to the law library. 4 weeks later a business plan was created.

fields.title: Team Assemble
fields.content1: Nine started with 2 Engineers, 2 Business Students and a Physics student (Team of 5). Team started going through APIs to properly visualize business model. Branding sprint was conducted and initial identity was carved. Creating a business plan(Logo, Values, Market, Business Model) started collectively with the team.
fields.content2: As soon as you start working on your ideas, things start to come up. You realize that on your own you simply will not get very far (unless it is a drop shipping business). That is why you need to think of the people who could potentially join you. Assembling a team is something that should not be rushed, after all, you would prefer the people to care about what you all are about to do.
fields.content3: Ah! the honeymoon phase, when everything was just fun and exciting. The team spent many nights brainstorming ideas on paper. We wrote, and rewrote many documents, (we had 8 copies of the business plan and 10 logos done in the first month) and had a grand time doing so. Going into Summer '19, we were full of potential, ideas, and a little bit of degeneracy.

fields.title: Team Disassemble
fields.content1:
Team began with good momentum going into Summer '19. Our business team and development team worked hard on  attending networking events and developing the  first iteration of landing page with 9's upcoming brand. 

Towards the end of the summer, 3 of 5 members of the team were not present in Ottawa. The goal was to begin to work remotely.
fields.content2: The team does not always have to work together. Everyone has their own challenges to face: school, work, job interviews, family.  Do not expect people to be there 24/7 fixing every possibly issue that could come up. Appreciate their time & energy commitment, they could be doing anything else right now.
fields.content3: As people's lives got busy, it became harder to remain united and focused. When the work really starts, attitudes change and paths begin to show themselves. For our team, the paths began to split off at a fork. We got more focused on our personal lives and priorities changed, the team went through growing pains.

fields.title: Small Wins
fields.content1: Through the end of summer and start of fall, 9 began to gain momentum once again. Our business team was able to get us a meeting with the head of MoneyGram Canada & a Royal Bank of Canada (RBC) Commercial Account Manager. As a result, got an inside look into the financial services industry from a veteran and began on-boarding with RBC.  Networking events began to to shape up, we competed in 2 pitch competitions placing (3rd & 2nd) respectively.
fields.content2: As you work together you start picking up momentum and the more you do it the better you become at it. This is the stage of flow, where you are the most excited. Use all the energy you have as things are not always going to be the way they are now.
fields.content3: While I'm day drinking in Singapore, the team began to focus on the upcoming school semester, and 9 was put on the back burner. Things seemed bleak, but little did we know that our paths would be merging soon again. On a random call in September, the team is revitalized and I had to get back to work. We all have to be responsible at some point!

fields.title: Make ≠ Create
fields.content1: Riding the momentum of wins, 9 began to strategize their first official press release(our revelation to the world). Social media accounts were created and the scramble for content began. To this effect, we began a philosophical journey into how to convey finance information in a different/more appealing way. We were not putting any content out. We were just coming up with ideas and feeling satisfied. Zero execution at this point.
fields.content2: It went to your head. Small wins make you start imagining the future possibilities, or how what you are doing is meant to be, and how you will potentially take over the world and eventually overtake google. You become such a fanatic of your own ideas that you stop working, at least temporarily. You spend all your time thinking and defining what you are trying to do. This is a great stage, as it helps your realize your own potential but do not spend here too long.
fields.content3: The second honeymoon began. Nine began to have a visualized brand, and we made cool content with our brand image (infographics for family and RBC). This was cool, but much like talking with "the boys" about girls, it is nothing like the real thing.

fields.title: The Big L
fields.content1: Towards the end of the year, feeling good about our landing page and content strategy, we were hit with big losses. RBC on-boarding fell through as we were deemed outside their risk appetite (no experience). We did not qualify for one of the competitions were applied for. Finally, 2 of 5 members quit. Both happened to be on our development team and the  9Finance partnership agreement was dissolved. All of this happened in the span of a week.
fields.content2: You knew it was coming. Just yesterday it seemed like you were on top of the world and today everything is falling apart. Your Ideas are not groundbreaking and you are definitely not the smartest person in the room right now either, as your teammates are starting to quit(like you a little less). This stage either makes you or breaks you. Just like it takes balls to start something, it takes balls to continue when you take the L.
fields.content3: It seems the revitalization was premature after all. Change was brewing in the world, and the trade deadline was approaching. Two members took their talents elsewhere, but their actions had already impacted the team forever.

fields.title: Identity Crisis
fields.content1: After catching a fat L, the remaining 3 members of the team had to re-group. Landing page & product development stalled. None of remaining members had web development experience. A mini-crisis ensued, we have a budding content vault but a solid product idea with no way to execute. Do we pivot to a content company or find new developers to execute initial product idea?
fields.content2: This is what happens when you do not listen to yourself. As you start getting yourself together some of your old values & habits  have to go. Did you learn anything? Take a moment to ask yourself questions: What? How? Why? Can you avoid it next time?
fields.content3: Facing drastic change, the 9 team had to learn to play again. Many arguments took place and meetings ran drastically over time. We went back to the basics and had to focus on workflow and passing. The most important thing was that we were now being honest. Our ideas were not mature, our process was not complete, and we did not know exactly where we were going... but we knew it.

fields.title: Back to Work
fields.content1: 9 is a team of 3 with no web developer, how do we proceed? Is this the end of our journey ? We are going to try making content and a product. The team can become even more dynamic! This is an opportunity to learn WebDev and add to our skill arsenal, and so we begin again. With a fundamentally different view on Finance and a product that captures the zeitgeist. We are creating, making and executing.
fields.content2: "Congratulations" - you made it this far.  It seems like whatever you're up to actually matters to you. You're back back where you started. Repeat-Repeat-Repeat.
fields.content3: Turns out being honest sucks. It hurts, and fantasy is so much sexier. But our honesty meant that we could get to work. Real work, work that is tangible, work that can be read... like this sentence. Where this goes?... stay tuned to find out .
